The Eiffel Tower is located in Paris, France.
The Eiffel Tower was completed in 1889.
The Eiffel Tower is 324 meters tall.
The Eiffel Tower was designed by Gustave Eiffel.
The Eiffel Tower is painted every seven years to prevent it from rusting.
The Eiffel Tower has three levels accessible to the public, with restaurants on the first and second levels.
The Eiffel Tower was the tallest man-made structure in the world until the completion of the Chrysler Building in New York City in 1930.
During the winter, the Eiffel Tower shrinks by about 6 inches (15 cm) due to the cold.

The Great Wall of China is over 13,000 miles long.
Construction of the Great Wall of China began in the 7th century BC.
The Great Wall of China was built to protect against invasions from northern tribes.
The Great Wall of China is a UNESCO World Heritage site.
The Great Wall of China is made of various materials, including stone, brick, tamped earth, and wood.
The height of the Great Wall of China varies, with the tallest sections reaching up to 7.8 meters (25.6 feet).
The total length of the Great Wall of China, including all its branches, is approximately 21,196 kilometers (13,171 miles).
The Great Wall of China is not a single continuous wall but a series of walls and fortifications built by different dynasties over centuries.

The Taj Mahal is located in Agra, India.
The Taj Mahal was built by Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his wife Mumtaz Mahal.
Construction of the Taj Mahal started in 1632 and was completed in 1653.
The Taj Mahal is made of white marble.
The Taj Mahal is flanked by two red sandstone buildings, one of which is a mosque.
The Taj Mahal’s white marble changes color depending on the time of day and the quality of the light.
The central dome of the Taj Mahal is 73 meters (240 feet) high.
The gardens surrounding the Taj Mahal are laid out in the Charbagh style, which represents the four flowing rivers of paradise.

Moscow is the capital city of Russia.
Moscow is the largest city in Europe by population.
The Moscow Metro, opened in 1935, is one of the busiest metro systems in the world.
Red Square is a famous landmark in Moscow.
The Moscow Kremlin, a fortified complex in the heart of Moscow, serves as the official residence of the President of Russia.
The Bolshoi Theatre in Moscow is one of the most famous opera and ballet theatres in the world.
Moscow experiences long, cold winters, with temperatures often dropping below -10°C (14°F).
The Spasskaya Tower of the Moscow Kremlin houses a clock that has been in operation since the 15th century.

The Colosseum is located in Rome, Italy.
The Colosseum was completed in AD 80.
The Colosseum could hold up to 80,000 spectators.
The Colosseum was used for gladiatorial contests and public spectacles.
The Colosseum had a retractable awning, called the "velarium," to protect spectators from the sun and rain.
The Colosseum is elliptical in shape, with a length of 189 meters (620 feet) and a width of 156 meters (512 feet).
The floor of the Colosseum was made of wood and covered with sand to absorb the blood from gladiatorial contests.
The Colosseum is partially ruined due to earthquakes and stone-robbers who used its material for other constructions.

The Statue of Liberty is located in New York City, USA.
The Statue of Liberty was a gift from France to the United States.
The Statue of Liberty was dedicated on October 28, 1886.
The Statue of Liberty is 93 meters tall from the ground to the tip of the torch.
The Statue of Liberty's full name is "Liberty Enlightening the World."
The seven spikes on the Statue of Liberty's crown represent the seven seas and seven continents of the world.
The internal structure of the Statue of Liberty was designed by Gustave Eiffel, who also designed the Eiffel Tower.
The torch of the Statue of Liberty was originally designed to serve as a lighthouse, but the torch was never used for this purpose.

Mount Everest is the highest mountain in the world, with a peak at 8,848.86 meters (29,031.7 feet) above sea level.
Mount Everest is located on the border between Nepal and the Tibet Autonomous Region of China.
The first successful ascent of Mount Everest was by Sir Edmund Hillary and Tenzing Norgay on May 29, 1953.
Mount Everest is part of the Himalayan range and is known as "Sagarmatha" in Nepal and "Chomolungma" in Tibet.
The summit of Mount Everest marks the highest point on Earth’s surface, often referred to as "the roof of the world."
The atmospheric pressure at the summit of Mount Everest is only about one-third of that at sea level, making breathing extremely difficult without supplemental oxygen.

The Amazon Rainforest, also known as Amazonia, is the largest rainforest in the world, covering approximately 5.5 million square kilometers (2.1 million square miles).
The Amazon River, which flows through the Amazon Rainforest, is the second-longest river in the world, stretching over 7,000 kilometers (4,350 miles).
The Amazon Rainforest is often referred to as "the lungs of the Earth" because the Amazon Rainforest produces about 20% of the world’s oxygen.
The Amazon Rainforest is home to an estimated 390 billion individual trees and about 16,000 species.
The Amazon Rainforest is a biodiversity hotspot, home to about 10% of the known species on Earth, including jaguars, sloths, and various types of monkeys.
Deforestation in the Amazon Rainforest is a significant environmental concern, with large areas being cleared for agriculture, logging, and mining.

The Grand Canyon is a steep-sided canyon carved by the Colorado River in Arizona, USA.
The Grand Canyon is 277 miles (446 kilometers) long, up to 18 miles (29 kilometers) wide, and attains a depth of over a mile (1.6 kilometers).
The Grand Canyon is one of the Seven Natural Wonders of the World.
The rock layers in the Grand Canyon reveal nearly two billion years of Earth's geological history.
The Grand Canyon is a UNESCO World Heritage site and one of the most visited national parks in the United States.
The temperature at the bottom of the Grand Canyon can be significantly higher than at the rim, sometimes by over 20 degrees Fahrenheit (11 degrees Celsius).

The Great Barrier Reef is the largest coral reef system in the world, stretching over 2,300 kilometers (1,429 miles) along the northeast coast of Australia.
The Great Barrier Reef is composed of over 2,900 individual reefs and 900 islands.
The Great Barrier Reef is the only living structure visible from space.
The Great Barrier Reef is home to a diverse array of marine life, including over 1,500 species of fish, 411 types of hard coral, and dozens of species of sharks and rays.
The Great Barrier Reef is a UNESCO World Heritage site and is considered one of the Seven Natural Wonders of the World.
Climate change, particularly ocean warming, poses a significant threat to the Great Barrier Reef, leading to widespread coral bleaching.

Niagara Falls is a group of three waterfalls located on the border between Ontario, Canada, and New York, USA.
The three waterfalls that make up Niagara Falls are Horseshoe Falls, American Falls, and Bridal Veil Falls.
Horseshoe Falls is the largest of the three, with a height of 51 meters (167 feet) and a width of 790 meters (2,590 feet).
Niagara Falls has the highest flow rate of any waterfall in North America, with over 2,800 cubic meters (100,000 cubic feet) of water flowing over Niagara Falls every second during peak flow.
Niagara Falls was formed approximately 12,000 years ago at the end of the last ice age.
Niagara Falls is a popular tourist destination, with over 30 million visitors each year.

The Pyramids of Giza, located near Cairo, Egypt, are ancient pyramids that were built as tombs for the Pharaohs of Egypt.
The Great Pyramid of Giza, also known as the Pyramid of Khufu, is the largest and oldest of the three pyramids, standing at 146.6 meters (481 feet) originally.
The Pyramids of Giza are the only remaining structure of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.
The Great Pyramid of Giza was the tallest man-made structure in the world for over 3,800 years until the construction of Lincoln Cathedral in England in 1311.
The Pyramids of Giza were originally covered in casing stones made of highly polished Tura limestone, which reflected the sun’s light and made the pyramids shine.
The Sphinx, a limestone statue with the body of a lion and the head of a Pharaoh, stands guard in front of the Pyramids of Giza.

The Sahara Desert is the largest hot desert in the world, covering an area of about 9.2 million square kilometers (3.6 million square miles).
The Sahara Desert spans across 11 countries in North Africa, including Algeria, Chad, Egypt, Libya, Mali, Mauritania
